Happy Friday and welcome back to our 102nd Weekly Dose of Optimism.
We=E2=80=99re back at it again. While many VCs are off galavanting in Europ=
e, we=E2=80=99re lucky that the researchers and scientists had a very busy =
week. They solved decades old math problems, got funding for quantum lasers=
, figured out how to edit genes in the microbiome, discovered a new super-E=
arth, and much more. These folks just can=E2=80=99t stop, won=E2=80=99t sto=
p.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Write of Passage [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/0a6d55e6-db4f-4d00-a1e0-6c4f8b85b0a0?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
No single investment of time or money has improved my life as much as David=
 Perell=E2=80=99s Write of Passage [ https://substack.com/redirect/0a6d55e6=
-db4f-4d00-a1e0-6c4f8b85b0a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Now, you can get David=E2=80=99s insights into writ=
ing for free with Writing Examples [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3c7f9c0=
-b4d6-47f2-9fff-a4d34ca4e965?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Writing is a multiplier. Whatever your passion or skill is, the ability to =
write about it clearly means your ideas and work will reach more people, an=
d resonate with them more strongly. One well-written essay, read by the rig=
ht people, can change your life. And writing that essay isn=E2=80=99t as ha=
rd as you think.=C2=A0
David is obsessed with writing; more specifically, he=E2=80=99s obsessed wi=
th helping people become great writers.=C2=A0 His podcast, How I Write [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/6c72d4a8-de2f-46fe-b51e-de7a76a3f558?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is one of my fa=
vorites, because he asks questions that only an obsessive could, and the an=
swers he pulls out of guests have changed the way I write.=C2=A0
With Writing Examples [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3c7f9c0-b4d6-47f2-9f=
ff-a4d34ca4e965?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], he=E2=80=99s delivering those insights straight to your inbox. D=
avid recently started the free weekly newsletter to study history=E2=80=99s=
 greats and teach you how to write like they do. Writing Examples [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/c3c7f9c0-b4d6-47f2-9fff-a4d34ca4e965?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is jam-packed with le=
ssons on writing, delivered in the way you wish you=E2=80=99d always been t=
aught.=C2=A0
I learned to be a better writer from David, and now you can too, for free. =
Trust me, Writing Examples [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3c7f9c0-b4d6-47=
f2-9fff-a4d34ca4e965?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] will make you a better writer, and that will make you a bett=
er=E2=80=A6 everything.=C2=A0=C2=A0
(1) With Fifth Busy Beaver, Researchers Approach Computation=E2=80=99s Limi=
ts [ https://substack.com/redirect/df4bec20-67fd-46e1-b686-f498c8561f63?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ben Brubaker for Quanta Magazine
Today, the team declared victory [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9cb2dd7-3=
e8b-42e6-925e-1c6ead7f4754?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. They=E2=80=99ve finally verified the true value of a =
number called BB(5), which quantifies just how busy that fifth beaver is. T=
hey obtained the result =E2=80=94 47,176,870 =E2=80=94 using a piece of sof=
tware called the Coq proof assistant [ https://substack.com/redirect/0f4786=
af-5956-4671-894a-3cda07149e63?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which certifies that mathematical proofs are free=
 of errors.
Researchers have identified the fifth "busy beaver" number, BB(5), proving =
it to be 47,176,870 steps. A busy beaver number, denoted as BB(n), is a con=
cept from theoretical computer science related to Turing machines. For a gi=
ven number of states n, the busy beaver number BB(n) represents the maximum=
 number of steps that any n-state Turing machine can take before halting, s=
tarting with a blank tape. In overly simple terms, it=E2=80=99s the maximum=
 number of steps the most active simple computer program with a given numbe=
r of rules can take before stopping.
Discovering busy beaver numbers is important because it shows the limits of=
 what simple computer programs can do and helps researchers understand the =
boundaries of computation. The recently discovered 5th busy beaver number i=
s much larger and more complex to find than the previous ones, highlighting=
 the complexity and unpredictability of increasingly advanced computers.
You won=E2=80=99t see any new AI model or other advance system immediately =
working this research into products, but the discovery should influence the=
oretical CS and is just another example of what a motley crew of researcher=
s can accomplish.=20
What makes the discovery even more amazing is that it was discovered a sort=
 of decentralized team of amateur mathematicians =E2=80=94 who in their fre=
e time from running software companies, completing dissertations and the li=
ke =E2=80=94 decided to take on a decades old theoretical math problem. Sta=
rting to believe that motley internet research teams can solve any problem =
thrown at them.
(2) DARPA's military-grade 'quantum laser' will use entangled photons to ou=
tshine conventional laser beams [ https://substack.com/redirect/23faa81c-a5=
2a-487c-8b54-c0b4b018de2a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Owen Hughes for Live Science
The U.S. Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) has awarded a $1=
 million grant to scientists building a prototype "quantum photonic-dimer l=
aser" that uses quantum entanglement to "glue" light particles together and=
 generate a highly concentrated laser beam.
Frickin=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Claser=E2=80=9D beams!
DARPA is funding the development of a "quantum photonic-dimer laser" that u=
ses quantum entanglement to bind photons together, creating a highly concen=
trated and stable laser beam. The new =E2=80=9Cquantum laser=E2=80=9D shoul=
d be able to maintain strength and precision over longer distances, as comp=
ared to traditional laser beams. The new laser=E2=80=99s military applicati=
ons are obvious =E2=80=94 cutting through fog, advanced surveillance, etc=
=E2=80=A6which is why DARPA is funding it =E2=80=94 but a quantum laser wou=
ld also have real world applicability in a number of fields such as quantum=
 computing, telecommunications, and medical imaging.=20
So what is a quantum laser and how is it different from a traditional laser=
? A traditional laser works by exciting electrons in atoms, making them rel=
ease photons in a synchronized way. These photons bounce between mirrors in=
side the laser, creating a concentrated beam of light. Quantum lasers, howe=
ver, use a special property called quantum entanglement. It links pairs of =
photons together, so they behave like a single unit. This makes the light b=
eam stronger and more precise because the linked photons help protect each =
other from interference.
After finishing up Dark Matter a couple of weeks ago, I can stop thinking a=
bout quantum entanglement. I guess the DARPA folks caught the series, too!
(3) Scientists edit the genes of gut bacteria in living mice [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/268e96be-5ba0-4c05-a3ff-9b74dca33549?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gemma Conroy for Nature
Scientists have designed a gene-editing tool that can modify bacterial popu=
lations in the gut microbiome [ https://substack.com/redirect/9057ec07-ef7a=
-4a1f-ab09-0bbe1c672f5f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of living mice
Tummy issues might have an issue of their own to deal with.
Scientists used a gene 'base editor' to successfully modify a gene in over =
90% of  E. coli bacteria in the gut of living mice, without causing harmful=
 side effects. Specifically, the base editor changed a DNA base (A to G) in=
 the bacteria's gene that produces =CE=B2-lactamases, enzymes responsible f=
or E. coli=E2=80=99s antibiotic resistance. Essentially, we now have a gene=
 editing tool capable of safely and effectively modifying bacteria in the g=
ut microbiome.
While the team showed the base editor=E2=80=99s efficacy in targeting E. co=
li bacteria in mice, the same methodology could be used to target any numbe=
r of bacterial strains or diseases in the gut microbiome. Importantly, the =
new methodology uses bacteriophage to reach gut bacteria and prevents the s=
pread of the edited genes.
Our gut microbes could soon be getting a genetic upgrade, flushing our tumm=
y issues down the toilet.
(4) Transmission Spectroscopy of the Habitable Zone Exoplanet LHS 1140 b wi=
th JWST/NIRISS [ https://substack.com/redirect/c94fee3a-f20f-45b1-bb61-4127=
69622f62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Cadieux et al from Universit=C2=B4e de Montr=C2=B4eal
Our JWST observations of LHS 1140b rule out the mini-Neptune scenario, plac=
ing it firmly in the super-Earth category.
Hell yeah. We may have another super-Earth!
Using the James Webb Space telescope, a team of scientists studied LHS 1140=
b, a planet 48 light years away and has decided it=E2=80=99s a potential su=
per-Earth. A super-Earth is a type of planet larger than Earth but signific=
antly smaller than Neptune, and is typically typically characterized by roc=
ky compositions and potentially habitable conditions. The recent observatio=
ns led the team to rule out LHS 1140b as mini-Neptune and to label it as a =
potential super-Earth.
LHS 1140b is 1.73 times larger and 5.6 times heavier than Earth, and was fo=
und to likely have a thick nitrogen-rich atmosphere. This observations hint=
 at LHS 1140b possibly having an ice world-like surface with an ocean on it=
s dayside. Together, the atmosphere and potential ocean, make LHS 1140b a p=
romising candidate for habitability. Now when I say habitability, it=E2=80=
=99s not like we can just shoot humans up there to build a civilization =E2=
=80=94 it would take our most advanced spacecraft over 100,000 years to rea=
ch LHS 1140b =E2=80=94 but understanding habitability deepens our understan=
ding of potential for life elsewhere in the universe.
Bonus: A.I. Helped Spot a Copper Bonanza. It Could Transform More Than Mini=
ng. [ https://substack.com/redirect/05c78049-322d-4454-8c1d-09bfc18137da?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Bearak for The New York Times
On Thursday, their company, KoBold Metals, informed its business partners t=
hat their find is likely the largest copper discovery in more than a decade=
=2E According to their estimates, revie=
wed by The New York Times, the mine wo=
uld produce at least 300,000 tons of copper a year once fully operational. =
That corresponds to a value of billions of dollars a year, for decades.
Packy here. In April, I wrote a Deep Dive on Earth AI [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/62f162e3-e2d9-4f06-9304-e07bd70980e0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a Not Boring Capital portfolio c=
ompany that is exploring and drilling for critical metals. Its AI model pre=
dicts the location of deposits, and its drilling platform verifies them 4x =
faster and 4x more cheaply. It=E2=80=99s a killer combo: the company has al=
ready made three discoveries when a traditional explorer is successful if i=
t makes just one.=20
In that piece, I mentioned another mining startup, KoBold Metals, writing:=
=20
That leaves KoBold, which is by far the most legitimate and fascinating of =
the startup competitor set. Founded in 2018, the company raised $195 millio=
n at a $1 billion post-money valuation from a16z, Breakthrough Energy, Bill=
 Gates, Jeff Bezos, and T. Rowe Price last year=E2=80=A6
While its site touts its exploration efforts, interestingly, it seems to be=
 focused midstream on the development stage. Last year, it acquired [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/7f049c61-bb70-4c63-b5de-38f510e00a7b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] the potentially ver=
y large Mincomba Copper deposit in Zambia, and is currently exploring and d=
rilling onsite to prove feasibility on the deposit. The company=E2=80=99s P=
resident, Josh Goldman, said that it looks to be similar to the Kakula mine=
 across the border in the Democratic Republic of Congo in size and grade, w=
hich is notable because that mine produced nearly 400,000 tons of copper la=
st year, which would translate to $3.6 billion in annual revenue at a coppe=
r price of $9,000 per ton.
It looks like the potentially very large mine has turned into a very large =
mine. Yesterday, The New York Times reported that KoBold=E2=80=99s feasibil=
ity studies found deposits that would support at least 300,000 tons per yea=
r, the largest copper mine discovered in the past decade. A third party rep=
ort that The Times viewed was slightly more conservative, but in line with =
that number.
To put the discovery in perspective, it=E2=80=99s enough copper for 100 mil=
lion EV batteries over the next two decades of production. And at 300,000 t=
ons per year at current prices of $9,695 per ton, it represents a roughly $=
3 billion annual revenue opportunity for KoBold for decades to come.=20
Seeing the news made me happy for a number of reasons.=20
First, it=E2=80=99s a solid proof point that mining companies can use moder=
n technology to make valuable and previously overlooked or uneconomical dis=
coveries. As The Times wrote, =E2=80=9CThe area of Zambia where it was foun=
d is known for copper. In fact, its name is Copperbelt Province. Still, nob=
ody had been able to home in on this mile-deep vein until KoBold did, right=
 under everyone=E2=80=99s noses.=E2=80=9D
Second, it=E2=80=99s another great example of Robert Zubrin=E2=80=99s maxim=
: =E2=80=9CThere are no natural resources. There are only natural raw mater=
ials. It is human creativity that transforms raw materials into resources t=
hrough technological innovations.=E2=80=9D
Third, it shows that investors can make real money investing in Techno-Indu=
strials, companies that use modern technology to take on large, established=
 industries and win. Mining is one of the most underinvested categories in =
tech, but if KoBold is able to successfully mine its Zambian deposits, let =
alone many others it=E2=80=99s currently exploring, the category may produc=
e one of the biggest outcomes in recent venture memory.=20
The more successful Techno-Industrials, the more money there will be for en=
trepreneurs who want to go after the really big, hard problems, even if the=
y look nothing like the big tech winners of the past couple decades.
Bonus: Neuralink Update
Just Elon being Elon, amiright?
Musk and some of the Neuralink team jumped on an awkwardly-positioned video=
 presentation of sorts to deliver some pretty mind-blowing updates on the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s progress and future plans.
In terms of progress, at this point we=E2=80=99ve all seen the videos of No=
land Arbaugh playing videos games and surfing the web using only his brain.=
 The team has identified some improvements from that first implant and has =
plans to start working with more patients. Looking forward, Neuralink prese=
nted plans for vision restoration, prosthetics interfacing, and generally s=
caling up the number of patients it=E2=80=99s able to serve.
Specifics of the update aside, it=E2=80=99s still wild that Musk is able to=
 get into the weeds like he did in this video. The guy runs the world=E2=80=
=99s largest EV and private space companies, as well as the world=E2=80=99s=
 most dizzying social media platform (among some other side bets like xAI a=
nd The Boring Company.) I sometime complain that I have to dedicate a coupl=
e of hours a week to writing a newsletter while also running a small creati=
ne gummy company. Some folks just really do be built different.
 Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all. Thanks to Write of Passage [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/0a6d55e6-db4f-4d00-a1e0-6c4f8b85b0a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for sponsoring!
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

