, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">DARPA i=
s funding the development of a &quot;quantum photonic-dimer laser&quot; tha=
t uses quantum entanglement to bind photons together, creating a highly con=
centrated and stable laser beam. The new &#8220;quantum laser&#8221; should=
 be able to maintain strength and precision over longer distances, as compa=
red to traditional laser beams. The new laser&#8217;s military applications=
 are obvious &#8212; cutting through fog, advanced surveillance, etc&#8230;=
which is why DARPA is funding it &#8212; but a quantum laser would also hav=
e real world applicability in a number of fields such as quantum computing,=
 telecommunications, and medical imaging. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>So wh=
at is a quantum laser and how is it different from a traditional laser? A t=
raditional laser works by exciting electrons in atoms, making them release =
photons in a synchronized way. These photons bounce between mirrors inside =
the laser, creating a concentrated beam of light. Quantum lasers, however, =
use a special property called </span><em>quantum entanglement</em><span>. I=
t links pairs of photons together, so they behave like a single unit. This =
makes the light beam stronger and more precise because the linked photons h=
elp protect each other from interference.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>After finishing up </span><em>Dark Matter </em><span>a couple of weeks ago=
, I can stop thinking about quantum entanglement. I guess the DARPA folks c=
